# insurance company has an conservative investment portfolio
Every insurance company has an investment portfolio, that’s the whole point of insurance companies. You collect money, hold it, and then pay it out when someone collects insurance. Yes, insurance companies make underwriting profit, the difference between money collected and that paid out. However, the main profit is from using the collected money and invest it and earn returns from the market. Insurance companies together with pensions and churches are some of the biggest non-finance/government institutional investors that exist.

Typically, their portfolios are more conservative relative. Their whole goal is to make steady returns on a HUGE sum of money. A small percentage of a big amount is a big profit. They invest in anything and everything, but conservatively. I haven’t worked for an insurance companies portfolio management, but I’ve worked on the other side (asset management sales trying to get insurances to invest in our fund). We would have to fill in super complex and detailed questionnaires and pass them to even be considered as an investment opportunity, followed by multiple lengthy interviews/discussions.

I’d recommend insurance portfolio management to anyone who loves portfolio management and a good work/life balance, but doesn’t want the intensity of working at an asset manager or hedge fund. From what I’ve seen, the people who work in the investment teams of insurances/pensions/governments/churches/etc. typically stay with the same company for much longer than those at financial services companies.


